Introduction¶

In this project, I will explore a dataset of Prosper Loan data, which contains 113,937 rows and 81 columns. I will pick some of the variables that are related to Default to analyze. I will first do some data wrangling and cleaning, and then move on to EDA using different types of charts to explore relationships between/among variables, and hopefully find out which variables can best predict the Default.

Data Wrangling, Assesing, & Cleaning¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 listings in the dataset with 81 features. Most variables are numeric, some are categorical, boolean and date. Variables like ProsperRating (Alpha) and IncomeRange can be ordered factor variables with the following levels.

ProsperRating (Alpha): HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA (worst to best)

IncomeRange: Not employed, \$0, \\$1-\$24,999, \\$25,000-\$49,999, \\$50,000-\$74,999, \\$75,000-\$99,999, \\$100,000+

Some of the variables have a lot of null values, such as variables prosperrating and prosperscore, which I'll need to deal with later.

Some variables are not of much use, such as listingkey, listingnumber, of other identifiers. These columns I will remove later.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting whether a loan would default or not, which is the LoanStatus variable.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that variables related to borrowers' personal situation would have effect on default, such as EmploymentStatus, CreditScoreRangeLower/Upper, DelinquenciesLast7Years, IncomeRange, etc. Because a borrower's financial status will have huge effect on their ability to pay loans. There are so many variables to explore in this dataset, maybe I can do some feature engineering as well.

Now it's time for some cleaning job. I will drop columns that I immediately know I won't need, and then deal with categorical variables first. After that, I will deal with float and int variables based on the order.

Since I'm interested to find out which variables are more correlated to become default or not, so I can't really use rows with loanstatus = current. And ideally, there are only 2 loan status: 1 & 0, where 1 means default, and 0 means no default. But from the value counts here, we can see there are more than 2 states, so for my analysis, I will assume that all past due loans are going to default, and I will ignore rows with loan status as current, cancelled, and finalpaymentinprogress. And I will encode completed as 1, all past dues as 0.

When income > 1, average borrower rate tend to go down as imcome range goes up. Not employed group tend to have higher borrowerate than any other groups, which makes sense. Which income group has the highest default rate?¶

Now, we know that the highest default rate did not come from income range \$25,000 - \\$49,999, it's actually come from Not Employed group and $0 group, which kind of makes more sense now, because people that's not employed and not having income might lead to their financial crisis, which could increase the possibility of not being able to pay the loan. Even though \$0 group has lower borrowerrate, they still were more likely to be defaulted. But then, Not display group's average default rate is lower than \\$0 - \$49,999, which makes me wonder maybe that group actually has income.

Conclusion¶

After univariate, bivariate, and multivarite analysis, I have explored the correlation between Default and some variables of interest. I've found out that if I want to predict a loan's going to be default or not, I can start by using variables such as borrower rate, income range, credit score, listing type, state, and debt to income ratio in the model.
